assoc_actor_1: 48 Cantones of Totonicapan; Maya Indigenous Group (Guatemala); Labor Group (Guatemala); Indigenous Group (Guatemala)
notes: On 19 October 2023, in Guatemala City, Guatemala, 60 thousand people, including members of the United Markets of Guatemala protested to demand the resignation of the Solicitor General and the head of the Special Prosecutor Against Impunity (FECI). In addition, they asked for the resignation of the president of the Chamber of Deputies and respect for the results of the presidential election. They marched through Aguilar Batres and Bolivar Avenue, gathered at the Central Park, to arrive at the Prosecutor's Office where the indigenous leaders are protesting. Protesters also gathered in Colonia Atlantida. They also demanded the annulment of the law initiative that would subject markets to tax control, which would affect informal business, as well as the annulment of the article 14 of the Organic Law of the Public Prosecutor's Office that states that the general attorney cannot be removed unless they have been convicted of an international crime while exercising their office. Q'eqchi', Poqomchi', Achi y other Indigenous groups of different regions left their communities the previous night to join the protest in front of the Prosecutor's Office. There were blockades in Street 32 and Petapa Avenue in zone 12. This is part of a wave of nation-wide demonstrations called by the 48 Cantones de Totonicapan (Maya indigenous group) (coded separately).

notes: On 10 October 2023, in Guatemala City, Guatemala, members of the 48 Cantones de Totonicapan (Maya indigenous group) staged protests to demand the resignation of the Solicitor General and the head of the Special Prosecutor Against Impunity (FECI). In addition, they asked for the resignation of the president of the Chamber of Deputies and respect for the results of the presidential election. Protests were mentioned at the crossroad between Calzada Roosevelt and avenida 1 in zone 7, in front of El Guarda market (zone 11), on Marti street (zone 2), on Petapa avenue (zone 12), in Colonia 4 de Febrero, on the Incienso Bridge and in zones 15, 3, 8, 6, and 18. In the Bethania neighborhood (zone 7) police forces were present but people on motorcycles surrounded them and prevented them from approaching the demonstrators (no mention was made of any direct interaction) who blocked the road with a trailer. One of the motorcyclists crashed into the police officers although it was an accident. This is part of a wave of nation-wide demonstrations (coded separately).
